  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Reductive Supplementation Pattern</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Beta-carotene:</strong> Observational benefit in food → isolated supplement → ATBC trial (n=29,133) found 18% increased lung cancer incidence in supplemented group</li>
    <li><strong>Resveratrol:</strong> Red wine observational data → isolated polyphenol → clinical trials consistently failed to replicate cardiovascular benefits</li>
    <li><strong>Omega-3s:</strong> Dietary fish observational benefit → isolated supplements → ASCEND (n=15,480) and VITAL (n=25,871) produced mixed, modest results</li>
    <li><strong>Probiotics:</strong> Fermented food observational and RCT benefit → isolated strains in capsules → no comparable multi-pathway effect demonstrated in head-to-head evidence</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-epistemological-close" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Else Are We Extracting</h2>
  <p>The supplement industry did not lie about probiotics. It identified a real biological phenomenon — the association between live fermented cultures and improved metabolic and immune markers — extracted one variable from a complex system, and sold that variable as equivalent to the whole. The marketing was not fraudulent. The science was reductive. The distinction is important, because reductive science is harder to prosecute and easier to repeat.</p>
  <p>The mechanism, when we look for it, is always in the complexity we discarded. Beta-carotene works differently in the presence of the other 600 carotenoids in a carrot. Resveratrol is one of several hundred polyphenols in a grape skin, and its bioavailability from food is different from its bioavailability from a capsule. The omega-3s in fatty fish arrive alongside selenium, vitamin D, and a protein matrix that may modulate their metabolism. And the bacteria in kimchi arrive inside a lactic acid environment, embedded in a partially hydrolyzed food matrix, accompanied by bioactive peptides and organic acids that have independent biological activity. Strip out the context and you have a different thing. You may have a useful thing — the evidence for specific probiotic strains in specific clinical conditions, including <em>C. difficile</em> recurrence and antibiotic-associated diarrhea, is legitimate and should not be dismissed. But you do not have the food.</p>
  <p>The question worth sitting with is not whether to eat kimchi. It is what else we are currently extracting, bottling, and selling at a $50 billion annual premium — while the evidence for the whole food sits quietly in the data, waiting for someone to run the trial. Nutritional science has a long history of answering that question badly, and a short history of noticing it has done so. The probiotic capsule is the current answer. It probably will not be the last one.</p>
</section>

